post_text: During Think Tank today, 4th grade students were challenged to critically think and problem solve through a tricky scenario. Their hiking team had a member fall while hiking El Capitan. The team didn't take a rope. They had to devise a 'rope' from the materials given that would rescue their stranded friend with a broken leg. He was 5 feet down on a ledge. They got points for length, strength, and teamwork. All did an excellent job! #GrowingThinkers @ TES! ♥️

post_text: Here is a quick update and a few pictures of our final construction projects. The new main gym entrance and restrooms are moving along nicely and are on schedule to be completed mid November. The new HS classrooms and offices are complete and look fantastic. We have brick going up on the practice gyms and expect them to be completed in December. The newer portion of the Swinburn campus that we kept is providing a lot flexibility with additional space for classrooms, training and testing. Thank you TISD community for your support with these projects.

post_text:
I am very pleased to announce that Dixie Johnson will take over at Tulia High School as the new Principal starting on Monday, July 13th. Mrs. Johnson has been with the Tulia ISD for 10 years as a Diagnostician and Director of Special Education. She has a total of 21 years in education and served students as an Elementary and Secondary Teacher for 11 years in Silverton ISD. Mrs. Johnson has a Bachelor of Science Degree from Wayland Baptist and a Masters of Education Degree from West Texas A&M University. Her certifications include Reading, ESL, Special Education, Principal and Diagnostician.

Students and staff will be in good hands with Mrs. Johnson’s instructional focus and leadership experience. I have full confidence that she will provide strong leadership for staff, maximize the academic potential of our students and take Tulia High School to exemplary status as an A rated campus. Please help me welcome Mrs. Johnson to her new role as the Principal at THS.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in when available later this week. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
La Transferencia Electrónica de Beneficios por Pandemia (P-EBT, por sus siglas en inglés) es un beneficio de alimentos único para las familias que perdieron el acceso a comidas gratuitas o a precio reducido debido al cierre de las escuelas. A fin de mayo, las escuelas les enviarán instrucciones para realizar una solicitud a las familias elegibles para la P-EBT. La solicitud de la P-EBT estará disponible la primera semana de junio.

Los beneficios de alimentos de la P-EBT son para los niños que recibieron beneficios de alimentos del Programa Asistencial de Nutrición Suplementaria (SNAP, por sus siglas en inglés) para marzo de 2020 y para los niños que estén certificados para recibir comidas gratuitas o a precio reducido en Texas durante el año escolar 2019-20. Para obtener más información, visite: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

post_text:
Construction Update:

The TISD Construction projects are going very well. The original plan was to demolish the entire Swinburn campus and build the two new gyms just west of the HS cafeteria. Through considerable discussion, the TISD Board approved the relocation of the new gyms to be south of Swinburn gym where the playground is located. This decision will allow the District to demolish the older portion of Swinburn facing Dallas street and keep the wing facing the parking lot/Hornet Place for future classrooms and office space. Estimated date of completion for the new gyms will be December 2020.

The new classrooms and office space at the front of Tulia High School is coming along nicely. Brick is being laid on the front and looks fantastic. This addition will include eight remodeled classrooms, a dedicated counseling center and new office area. Estimated date of completion is August 2020.

Tulia ISD is pleased to announce Kaylee Rhoderick as the new Special Education Teacher. Mrs. Rhoderick graduated from West Texas A&M University with a Bachelor of Science in Agriculture Education in 2012. She taught previously in Dalhart ISD as a 7th grade science teacher, and is currently certified through the State of Texas to teach Agricultural Science and Technology.

Mrs. Rhoderick’s plans are to continue to seek certifications in numerous areas. Mrs. Rhoderick is working with students and staff to meet the needs of all students at Tulia High School. Please help us welcome her to the staff of Tulia ISD.

post_text:
Tulia ISD is pleased to announce and welcome Lindsay Coursey as a classroom teacher at Tulia Elementary School. Mrs. Coursey comes to us most recently from Perryton ISD, where she has been teaching 2nd grade for the past 8 years. Previous to her time at Perryton, she spent 4 years teaching Pre-K and 1st grade in Stinnett, for a total of 11 years in education.

Mrs. Coursey earned her Bachelor of Arts in Early Childhood Education from West Texas A & M University in 2008, and has been actively involved in education ever since. Her certifications include EC - 4th grade as well as an English as a Second Language certification.

We are thrilled to add Mrs. Coursey to the Tulia Elementary School family, as well as to Tulia ISD and to our community. Join us to extend a warm welcome to Mrs. Coursey and her family.

post_text:
Tulia ISD is pleased to announce and welcome Steven Coursey as the new Athletic Director and Head Football Coach. Mr. Coursey has served the students of Perryton ISD for the last 8 years with 4 years of experience as the Head Varsity Football Coach and Assistant Athletic Director. Prior to Perryton, Mr. Coursey was in Plemons-Stinnett-Phillips CISD from 2008-2012 as a teacher and coach. Mr. Coursey has experience as an Offensive Coordinator, Assistant Football (Receivers and Quarterbacks), Assistant Boys Basketball, JV Baseball, Varsity Assistant Baseball and Head Baseball Coach.

In addition to his coaching experience, Mr. Coursey has taught Algebra I, Algebra I EOC Remediation, RTI Math, Health and PE. He has a Bachelor of Science Degree in General Studies from West Texas A&M University and holds certifications in Mathematics 4-8, Health and PE (EC-12).

We are excited to have Mr. Coursey and his family join the TISD team. Please help us welcome the Coursey's to Tulia and Tulia ISD.

shared_text:
D'Lee Marble is with Sandra Wheeler Johnson.
February 15 at 9:48 PM ·

Tulia’s 46 CTE students did an amazing job at the SKILLSUSA Contest this weekend at South Plains College, in Levelland. These students competed in Automotive, Culinary, Forensics, Medical Terminology, and Welding against 1A to 6A schools.

Forensics Team placed 1st - Luke Unterkircher, Savannah Cooper, and Jackie Briones.

Medical Terminology students Patricia Glasscock 1st place, and Claire Johnson 2nd place.

Their projects all received 1st place and are State Bound: Savannah Cooper, Jackie Briones, Luke Unterkircher, Patricia Glasscock, and Zoee McCrary.

I am so proud of these students hard work and dedication. They all qualified for the State SkillsUSA Contest in Corpus.

shared_text:
Dennis Mccaslin is at The SEMA Show.
November 6, 2019 at 3:43 PM · Las Vegas, NV ·

First run under our belt, we didn’t do too well. Two of the boys didn’t get their tools loaded so we borrowed a few from Hereford to get us by. Rodney Ferguson is a stand up guy! He has helped us from the get go even knowing we are his competition. Thanks Rod! Even not having the tools we are used to the guys still ran the 4th fastest time of the day. We had some penalties so it wasn’t a clean run but the mistakes are some we almost never make so they should be easy to fix. I went shopping last night, so maybe we will have what we need to get us close to what we have been running. Thanks for all the support from home! My Town! Today is a new day!

post_text:
Please come out tomorrow if you can!

A message from Dennis McCaslin...

On Saturday October 5th, THS Hot Rodders of Tomorrow will be competing against two nationally qualified teams from Hereford. These are 3 of only 5 in all of Texas that qualified. The event will take place at 5pm at the Swisher County Airport. It’s free to watch, but we will be selling hamburger plates, in order to help fund our trip to Nationals. post_text:
The results are in!

The District, Tulia High School and Tulia Elementary improved by one letter grade; each going from a D rating to a C.

Tulia Junior High improved from an F rating (57) to a B rating (82)! This is a 25 point gain for the JH campus and unheard of across the state in just one year!

Tulia Junior High also received the following campus distinctions:
1) Academic Achievement in Science
2) Academic Achievement in Social Studies
3) Top 25% Academic Growth (Ranked # 3 out of 40 other demographically similar campuses)
4) Top 25% Closing the Gaps (Ranked # 4 out of 40 other demographically similar campuses)

Congratulations to our students, faculty and staff for making strong academic gains during the 2018-2019 school year. We've set our sights on becoming an A rated district and will use this momentum to continue building a high-level academic program for the community of Tulia.

Kids in Tulia ISD are winning!

How to view the live stream of Graduation tonight:

The easiest way to view the live stream tonight will be on Facebook. It'll show up in your feed if you follow the Tulia ISD page or you can search and go to Tulia ISD's Facebook page at 7 pm to find it.

If you go to http://www.tuliaisd.net , you'll get a pop-up with instructions on how to connect on there. The Tulia ISD website may be limited on screen size though.

With this being the 1st time we've tried livestreaming an event, please excuse any technical difficulties. We will have staff on hand to work out issues as they arise but hopefully all the planning and preparation into this will prevent any interruption.

We're excited to share this evening with you and show off our graduates! Congratulations Class of 2019!

post_text:
Annual Ag Safety Day at Swinburn today!

Progressive Agriculture Safety Days®

Recognized as the largest rural safety and health education program for children in North America, Progressive Agriculture Safety Days® are as fun as they are educational. These one-day events teach children lessons that help keep them and those around them safe and healthy.

At a Progressive Agriculture Safety Day, participants are divided into small groups of 10 to 15 that rotate between stations where lessons outlined in the Progressive Agriculture Safety Day Topics and Activities Manual are taught. To facilitate learning, educational, age-appropriate and fun hands-on activities and demonstrations are part of each lesson.

post_text:
Congratulations to Mr. Vasquez who was selected as a Mrs Baird's Teachers on the Rise for the month of March! He was selected because he is a teacher who goes above and beyond the call of duty and has a special impact on his students' lives.

He was nominated by Chris Chadwick.

How the Program Works
Every month during the school year, Mrs Baird's and United Supermarkets selects three winners-one in elementary, one in middle school/junior high, and one in high school. These winners can come from any school district in the area.

Teachers On The Rise winners receive great prizes including a $100 United Supermarkets Shopping Spree, a $100 AMEX gift card courtesy of Amarillo Custom Box Company, and a gift basket full of products and goodies from Mrs Baird's Bread. To encourage students to enter their teachers, we give each student who nominates a winning teacher a $50 VISA card!

We are just a few minutes from reaching the 33 minute mark. “

The Tulia Independent School District, Tulia Police Department, Swisher County Sheriff’s Department, Texas Department of Public Safety, and Texas Rangers are aware of the videos posted on Youtube concerning Tulia.

The person who posted the videos has been identified by law enforcement. This is not a local individual and has no ties to our community. The governmental entities do not believe there is an imminent threat however we are taking precautions to ensure the safety of our students and citizens.

We will keep you updated of any developments. Please report any unusual activity to the Tulia Police Department.

post_text:
"Student outcomes don't change until adult behaviors change".

This was the central theme of the two day Lone Star Governance training attended by all members of the Tulia ISD and Perryton ISD School Boards. Tulia and Perryton are the first schools in Region 16 and 17 to participate in the training. LSG is specifically designed for School Boards and is intended to provide a governance model that focuses on continuous academic improvement.

A big thank you to the TISD Board for investing in our students!

Go check out the Traveling Trailblazer TODAY at the Swisher County Library!

TAME's traveling Trailblazer is a 40 foot exhibit trailer that houses a variety of engineering and science exhibits targeted at students in grades 3-8. The Trailblazer is the only interactive science and engineering museum-on-wheels in Texas.

Price: Free
Hours: 9:30 am - 1:30 pm
Address: 127 SW 2nd St, Tulia, TX 79088

post_text: 🎶 Don't forget that our amazing Fightin' Hornet Band will be preforming at 2:30 today at Dick Bivins Stadium in Amarillo! 🎶 Please come support if you can and cheer them on to State! 🏆
shared_text:
Tulia ISD
October 26, 2017 at 3:06 PM ·

This past weekend our Fightin' Hornet Band competed at the Region 1 Marching Contest and earned 1st division ratings from all 3 judges! Our student musicians and their directors work tirelessly to master their craft and put on an amazing show!

They advanced to compete this Saturday, October 28th, in the Area Marching Contest at Dick Bivins Stadium in Amarillo at 2:30 pm.

They will battle bands from all across West Texas (and about half of the state) and take in home field advantage as the closest competitors, so come represent in large numbers and help push our Fightin' Hornet Band all the way to State! See you there!

Photo credit: Mr. Haynes

For more information about our facility needs and answers to why the Tulia ISD School Board has called for a Bond Election, please view this resource.

Remember that early voting is available 8:00 am to 5:00 pm Monday - Friday this week and next at the Health and Human Services Office located at 219 SE 2nd.

If you miss early voting, election day is November 7th from 7:00 am to 7:00 pm at the Health and Human Services Office (219 SE 2nd) and at the Administration Office of Tulia ISD (702 NW 8th).

post_text: On this election day...don't forget to go vote for Swinburn in the Red Ribbon Photo Contest!
shared_text:
REDRIBBON.ORG
Red Ribbon Campaign: Voting Page - Red Ribbon Photo Contest

Tulia ISD
November 4, 2016 at 9:47 PM ·

Vote for Us!

Swinburn entered a Red Ribbon Photo Contest. The winner is based on votes.

NOTES ABOUT VOTING
Voting is limited to one vote per entry per 24 hour period per person, so if someone votes at 7am on Monday, they will have to wait until 7:01am on Tuesday to vote again.

Please vote from a mobile device or on your home computer once a day until November 17th!

The following link will take you directly to Swinburn's entry: http://redribbon.org/vote/#view/0/4181686

The voting period will end on Thursday, November 17 at 11:59pm (ET).

Thanks for your support!!
